Macedonians will vote in referendum if they want to change the name of the country
Macedonian citizens voted in a referendum on Sunday if they wanted the country’s name to be changed to “the Republic of North Macedonia,” a change that would resolve a decade-old dispute with Greece that opposed its accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which includes a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the neighbouring country is a claim on its territory and has opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
The two governments agreed in June on the proposed new name, but opposition nationalists argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia’s Slavic majority population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign had cast doubt on the presence of the vote, as it was possible not to reach the minimum limit of 50%, necessary for the validation of the referendum.
The question on the ballot for the referendum will be: “Do you agree to join the EU and NATO, accepting the agreement with Greece?”.
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, say it is a price to be paid by Macedonia, one of the countries that resulted from the destruction of Yugoslavia, in order to be accepted into entities such as the EU and NATO.
“I am here today to vote for the future of the country, so that the young people of Macedonia live free under the umbrella of the European Union, because that means safer lives for all of us,” said the 79-year-old Olivera Georgijevska in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, quite a few members of parliament have said they will respect the result of the vote to make it decisive.
For the name to be changed, a two-thirds quorum in parliament is required.
The State Electoral Commission said no irregularities were reported until 1 p.m.
However, participation was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last 2016 parliamentary elections when 66% of the people with the right to vote showed up to vote.
“I came to vote for my children and for our place in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter from Skopje, the country’s capital.
On 30 September 2018, Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and their son Dusko voted in a referendum to change the name of Macedonia, which will allow him to join NATO and join the European Union.
In front of the Skopje parliament, the 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small scene and pulled chairs in front of the tents raised by those who will boycott the referendum.
“We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them with the top, not the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted by the name of Macedonia, we can go to other countries, such as China and Russia, and we can become part of the Eurasian Union."
Zaev said NATO membership would bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
“I think the majority will be in favor of changing the name, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favor of joining NATO and the EU,” Zaev said.
He said a result in favor of changing the name would be “confirmation of our future.”
According to a poll published last month by the Institute for Policy Research, between 30% and 43% of citizens with the right to vote will participate in the referendum, under the number of participants required.
According to another poll conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote for the change.
In order for the referendum to be valid, the vote must be 50% plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would represent the first serious blow to the pro-Western government’s policy since its takeover in May last year.
