And now, a page in our Sunday morning Almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago (and the count continues...), is the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the creation of the device known as the Geiger counter.
An essential device for science ever since, the Geiger counter has become essential for pop culture as it did in the 1950 film The Bells of San Coronado, in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans played cowboys with unlikely inclinations.
Man: “What else is that?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you wear these headphones, you can hear the effects of atoms emitted by radioactivity in minerals.”
Evans: “Yes, they hear a lot of sneezing!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before he turned 63.
But the invention that bears his name is still alive.
