Germany's new warship, postponed again
Germany’s newest naval frigate was supposed to be put into operation in 2014 to replace the Cold War warships, but this will not happen until next year, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The entry into service of the "Rheinland-Pfalz" ship, the standard ship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg frigate class, has now been delayed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, citing a military spokesman.
The vessel should have been introduced into the maritime forces in 2014, but problems arising after delivery affected this ambitious project.
The four vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old frigates of the Bremen class.
They are supposed to be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-vas missiles, as well as stealth technologies, which provide a low radar, infrared and acoustic footprint.
Other important features will include longer maintenance periods; it should be possible for the new frigates to be able to go on missions for two years without returning to the original port.
