The National Trust is spying on the secret life of the lilies.
New research that is being carried out on a property in the Scottish Highlands will reveal how bats use the environment to hunt prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these unprecedented flying mammals and will help future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland, will analyze common dwarf foxes and pygmy foxes, as well as eared foxes and water foxes from the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be located in key locations around the property to track the activity of lilies throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
Specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and which species emit certain sounds.
A map of the habitat and a report will be produced to create a detailed picture, on a scale, of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of lawn, and what is the best way to maintain forest land for foxes and other associated species.
Flea populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably in the last century.
They are endangered by the construction and development work that affects their nests, but also by the loss of habitat.
Both wind turbines and public lighting are risks, as are flies traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, but also attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who periodically conduct studies, control the nests, and sometimes perform rescue missions.
The organization created even the first and only flea reserve in Scotland, on the Thrave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland's ten flea species are found.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says this is the ideal territory for bats.
“Here at Thrave, the area is great for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand why they need to multiply.”
It stresses the importance of looking for butterflies before carrying out maintenance work on the properties, as simple unintentional destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and chickens, which can destroy the entire local population.
Lilies are protected, and killing, harassment or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don’t know how populations evolve for many of our species.”
