The number of North Korean refugees in South Korea has fallen since Kim Jong-un came to power seven years ago, a South Korean lawmaker said.
Park Byeong-seug, citing data from South Korea’s unification ministry, said that last year about 1,127 people fled the country, compared to 2,706 in 2011.
Park said the key factors were tighter border controls between North Korea and China and higher tariffs levied by those who illegally transport people across the border.
Pyongyang has not made any public comments.
A vast majority of refugees from the north are eventually granted South Korean citizenship, according to the report.
Seoul officials say more than 30,000 North Koreans have crossed the border illegally since the end of the Korean War in 1953.
Most flee through China, which has the longest border with North Korea and is easier to cross than the heavily demilitarized protected zone (DMZ) between the two sides of Korea.
China considers refugees to be illegal migrants rather than refugees, and often forcibly repatriates them.
Relations between the North and the South, which are still practically at war, have improved significantly in recent months.
Earlier this month, the leaders of the two countries met in Pyongyang for some discussions on the topic of denuclearisation negotiations.
This came after the historic meeting between U.S. President Donald Trump and Kim Jong-un in Singapore, when they agreed, in general terms, to work together for a nuclear-free Korean peninsula.
But on Saturday, North Korean Foreign Minister Ri Yong-ho accused that U.S. sanctions have caused a lack of progress since.
“If we can’t trust the United States, we won’t be able to trust our national security, and in such situations, under no circumstances will we be the first to disarm unilaterally,” Ri said in a speech to the United Nations General Assembly in New York.
