Pelosi made the comments Saturday in an interview at the Texas Tribune Festival in Austin, Texas.
“I can’t help but think that if she was a woman in this situation, she would have been declared “hysterical,” Pelosi said of her reaction to Kavanaugh’s testimony before the Senate Judiciary Committee, which took place on Thursday.
Kavanaugh denied allegations that he sexually harassed Christine Blasey Ford when they were teenagers.
During his opening statement, Kavanaugh was very excited, sometimes almost yelled and lost his voice due to emotions, while discussing his family and high school years.
He also explicitly denounced the Democrats on the committee, calling the accusations against “a grotesque and coordinated murder of character” organized by furious liberals that Hillary Clinton lost the 2016 presidential election.
Pelosi said he felt that Kavanaugh's testimony had shown that he could not serve in the Supreme Court because he had shown that he was biased against the Democrats.
“I think he disqualifies with those statements and the way he attacked the Clinton family and the Democrats,” she said.
Pelosi deviated from the subject when asked if she would try to suspend Kavanaugh if he would be confirmed and if Democrats would win a majority in the House of Representatives.
“I just want to say this: if he doesn’t tell the truth to Congress or the FBI, then it’s not appropriate, not just for the Supreme Court, but also for the court he’s in right now,” Pelosi said.
Currently, Kavanaugh is a judge in the District of Columbia Court of Appeals.
