How could the trade war between the United States and China be beneficial to Beijing?
The salvos that announced the start of the trade war between the United States and China have been overwhelming and, while there seems to be a long way to go before it ends, the disputes between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
US President Donald Trump issued the first warning earlier this year by imposing tariffs on key imports from China, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most important escalation occurred this week with new taxes, which affected products worth $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion), effectively applying taxes on half of all goods in China that arrive on U.S. territory.
Beijing has taken revenge each time, most recently imposing a tariff of between 5 and 10 percent on US products worth $60 billion.
China has warned it will respond to every blow from the United States and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economy will take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree to its demands, but publicly ceding to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, U.S. pressures on the trade war could positively support China in the long run, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision made in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic collapse in both countries would actually be more dangerous than what has been predicted so far,” said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher who focuses on Asia at the New American Security Center.
Syria Is Ready for Refugees to Return, Foreign Minister Says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country devastated by a war that has lasted more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the situation in the country is improving.
"Today, the conditions on the ground are more stable and safe, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists so that things return to normal.
The existing conditions allow the voluntary return of refugees to the country they have been forced to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and lives.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war broke out in 2011.
Six million people who continue to live in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive aid to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or assistance from some countries sponsored by the insurgency will not be accepted.
