Red tide news: concentrations decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows a general drop in red tide concentrations for certain areas of the Gulf of Tampa.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in areas in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
This red tidal inflorescence extends over a coastal area of approximately 210 km, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The spots can be found about 16 km across Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
The average concentrations found in the Charloer in Pinellas County or beyond were reported last week, as well as the low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, the bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, the bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, the bottom to high concentrations in Col County or in Sarasota County.
Irritation of the airways in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties continues to be reported.
No cases of respiratory tract irritation have been reported in the northwestern U.S. state of Florida in the past week.
